toxicities) were derived from the literature.
RESULTS: Median overall survival, QALYs, and total costs for the erlotinib-first 
strategy were 3.9 months, 0.33, and €15,233, respectively, compared with 4.4 
months, 0.35, and €15,363 for the chemotherapy-first strategy. There was no 
significant difference between the 2 strategies in term of cost-effectiveness 
(respectively €47,381 and €44,350 per QALY).
CONCLUSION: No difference in cost-effectiveness was found between an 
erlotinib-first strategy and a chemotherapy-first strategy in frail elderly 
patients with NSCLC.

